central and southern Italy, from <i>marra</i> ‘heap of stones’.","Italian, Galician, and Portuguese: from <i>marra</i> ‘hoe’, in Galician and Portuguese also ‘big mallet for breaking stones’ (from Latin <i>marra</i>), presumably a metonymic occupational name for one who made such implements or for one who used them."]},{"name":"Merrow","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Marrow  .","English: habitational name from Merrow in Surrey, apparently derived from Old English <i>mearg</i> ‘marrow, fat’, used figuratively to mean ‘fertile ground’.","Americanized form of French   Amirault   or of any of its altered forms. Compare   Meraw   and   Mero   4."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":2,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Marrow III was born in 1380, in London, Middlesex, 